Dataset Overview:¶

This dataset has 4 tables:

  • User table: introduces user profile including country, signup date, user id and company id
  • Event details table: describes each type of events and the platform that they take place
  • Company table: company id and its recorded type
  • Event table: events on platform from 2019 Feb to 2021 Feb

Data quality issues: the majority of dataset is quite clean and full, only contains some empty data in user and company table, such as 0.22% in SignupDate is empty, 0.19% in CompanyId is empty, 13.26% in Country is empty, 0.19% in RecordType is empty.

Investigation Overview:¶

4 tables described above are merged together to be looked at:

  • Trend of events throughout the whole period
  • Trend of users throughout the whole period
  • Developers' behaviors on platform (compared with other types of users)
  • Recommended KPIs in order to track growth of customer base

Definitions:¶

  • Active developer - original: a user that has performed at least one of four specific activities in the past 30 days
  • Active developer - adjusted in order to be tracked: a user that has performed at least one of four specific activities in one activity month
  • Developer: a user who's ever performed one developer activity throughout the whole period
  • Developer event: ModelDeployed, SandboxDeployed, TeamserverCommit, WmDeploySucceeded

Active means active in a reporting month instead of active in past 30 days.

# define pie chart function
def pie_plot(df1, df2, name1, name2):
    i = df1.shape[0]
    fig, ax =plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize = [10,8])

    ax[0].pie(df1['perc'], autopct="%.1f%%", explode=[0.05]*i, labels= df1['First_event'].values)
    ax[0].set_title('Top 4 event types of {:s}'.format(name1))
       
    ax[1].pie(df2['perc'], autopct="%.1f%%", explode=[0.05]*i, labels = df2['First_event'].values)
    ax[1].set_title('Top 4 event types of {:s}'.format(name2))
    
pie_plot(other_type, developer_type, 'other users', 'developers')
  • The 3 events that users perform after signup are similar.
  • Except other users also view app clicked (2.7%), while developer check app store download (1.6%).
  • The starting point of developers and other users are similar.

Recommended KPIs¶

MoM growth:¶

Def:

  • Track month over month growth rate of developers in customer base.
  • Use average mom growth rate from previous year as current year's target.

Benefits:

  • Useful when business is in climbing phase in order to track is the accelaration rate is slower, probably signaling entering another phase.
  • It can also be applied to YoY growth rate.

Developer committed time:¶

Def:

  • Track trend of customer developer's committed time as payment is monthly.

Benefits:

  • When customer developers who spend long time on platform increase, more revenue are generated, these customers also become more influential and loyal.

Takeaway:¶

  • Top users still concentrate more on non developer events.
  • Although developers are slightly bigger than other types of users throughout the whole period, they've very stable portion in customer base.
  • Partner is still the biggest type of user, followed by customer.
  • Signup boomed in 2019 Q1 and 2020 Jun, creating lots of events and users.
  • Netherlands is the biggest market, US and Germany have very big potential.
  • Developers turn to use more event sources and have more types of events than other type of users.
  • Most developers start developing immediately after signup, however after signing up for 1 year, there's still chance for a regular user to be a developer.
  • 2 KPIs are introduced.

Future touch points:¶

Due to limited time and information, this analysis focuses on some sides of events and user information only, for future analysis, below points are suggested:

  • Link users data to revenue model, such as type of user and their active time on platform
  • Keep track customers' committed time on platform in a long run, such as how often they have activity on platform
  • Keep track of other type of users, as they have chance to become developers
  • Retain newly signed up customers (if think about the extreme values they brought in)
